  "text": "HTTP filter factory registration and instantiation in Envoy follows a multi-stage process:\n\n## Factory Registration\n\nHTTP filter factories are registered at startup time using the templated Registry system. The core registry is implemented in `envoy/registry/registry.h` with the `Registry::FactoryRegistry<T>` template class, which maintains a static map of registered factory instances keyed by name. HTTP filter factories inherit from `Server::Configuration::NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory` (defined in `envoy/server/filter_config.h`) and are registered via the `Registry::RegisterFactory<T, Base>` template, typically using the `REGISTER_FACTORY` macro. Each factory factory registers itself with a category (\"envoy.filters.http\") for discovery.\n\n## Filter Chain Factory Creation\n\nWhen the HTTP connection manager is configured, the `Extensions::NetworkFilters::HttpConnectionManager::HttpConnectionManagerConfig` class (in `source/extensions/filters/network/http_connection_manager/config.h`) implements `Http::FilterChainFactory` and is responsible for creating HTTP filter chains. During initialization, the `HttpConnectionManagerConfig` constructor processes the filter configuration using `Http::FilterChainHelper<>` (defined in `source/common/http/filter_chain_helper.h`).\n\nThe `FilterChainHelper::processFilters()` method iterates through each configured HTTP filter in the configuration. For each filter, `FilterChainHelper::processFilter()` looks up the factory from the registry using `Registry::FactoryRegistry<>::getFactory()`, validates the configuration, and calls the factory's `createFilterFactoryFromProto()` method to obtain a `Http::FilterFactoryCb` (a std::function defined in `envoy/http/filter_factory.h`). These callbacks are stored in a `FilterFactoriesList`.\n\n## Per-Request Filter Instantiation\n\nWhen a new HTTP stream arrives on a connection:\n\n1. The `Http::ConnectionManagerImpl` class (in `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.h`) receives the new stream in the `newStream()` method, which creates a new `ActiveStream` structure.\n\n2. The `FilterManager` class (in `source/common/http/filter_manager.h` and `filter_manager.cc`) is responsible for managing the filter chain for that stream. Its `createFilterChain()` method is called, which invokes the `FilterChainFactory::createFilterChain()` method (delegating to `HttpConnectionManagerConfig`).\n\n3. `HttpConnectionManagerConfig::createFilterChain()` calls `FilterChainUtility::createFilterChainForFactories()`, which iterates through the stored filter factory callbacks and calls `FilterChainManager::applyFilterFactoryCb()` for each one.\n\n4. `FilterManager::applyFilterFactoryCb()` (at line 551 in filter_manager.cc) creates a `FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl` object (a nested class in `FilterManager` at line 913 in filter_manager.h) and calls the filter factory callback with this callbacks object.\n\n5. The filter factory callback instantiates the actual filter object and calls appropriate methods on `FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl` (such as `addStreamDecoderFilter()`, `addStreamEncoderFilter()`, or `addStreamFilter()`) to register the filter instance with the filter manager.\n\n6. These callback methods create `ActiveStreamDecoderFilter` and `ActiveStreamEncoderFilter` wrapper objects that manage the filter lifecycle and data flow through the chain.\n\nThe factory base classes in `source/extensions/filters/http/common/factory_base.h` provide common functionality for HTTP filter factory implementations, including `FactoryBase`, `ExceptionFreeFactoryBase`, and `DualFactoryBase` which support both downstream and upstream HTTP filters."
}

